  "prompt": "What happens to you if you try to walk around Mars without a spacesuit?",
  "response": "If you were to walk around on Mars without a spacesuit, you would quickly die due to several extreme environmental conditions:\n\n1. Lack of Atmospheric Pressure: Mars has an extremely thin atmosphere, about 1% as dense as Earth's. Without a pressurized suit, the low pressure would cause your body fluids to boil and tissues to expand, leading to rapid death.\n\n2. Extremely Low Temperature: Mars' average temperature is around -63\u00b0C (-81\u00b0F), which would cause immediate and severe frostbite and hypothermia.\n\n3. No Breathable Oxygen: Mars' atmosphere is mostly carbon dioxide, so you would quickly suffocate without an oxygen supply.\n\n4. Radiation Exposure: With no magnetic field and a very thin atmosphere, Mars receives much higher levels of cosmic and solar radiation, which would quickly cause radiation sickness.\n\n5. Decompression: The sudden exposure to such low pressure would cause your blood to vaporize and your body to essentially explode.\n\nThese conditions would cause death within seconds to minutes, depending on specific circumstances. A spacesuit is absolutely essential for human survival on Mars.",
